Introduction¶

In the dynamic and competitive world of online retail, understanding the intricate language of customer behavior is paramount for success (Smith, Jones & Brown, 2023). While traditional methods may focus on individual product selections, customers often weave a fascinating narrative through their purchases, combining items in unexpected yet insightful ways. This co-purchase behavior, revealing hidden relationships between seemingly disparate products, presents a valuable opportunity for businesses to gain a competitive edge.

Association rule mining emerges as a powerful tool for decoding this hidden language. This data mining technique allows us to unmask the intricate connections between products, unveiling patterns and trends that transcend individual purchases. By analyzing the tapestry of co-occurrences within customer transaction data, we can gain valuable insights into:

  • Complementary products: Discovering frequently bought-together items that suggest natural pairings or needs fulfillment, such as purchasing printer ink alongside printer paper.
  • Substitute products: Identifying products that serve similar purposes and are often purchased as alternatives, depending on factors like price or availability.
  • Category relationships: Revealing connections between products within the same category, like different types of vegetables or beverages, potentially indicating broader purchasing habits or seasonal trends.

My Objective in Project¶

This project delves into the application of association rule mining within the context of online retail. By analyzing customer purchase data, we aim to:

  • Identify hidden product relationships: Discover frequently co-purchased items that go beyond what might be readily apparent, potentially revealing complementary products, substitute items, or related categories.
  • Uncover product clusters: Group products that are frequently bought together, providing insights into customer preferences and shopping habits. This can help us understand how customers navigate product categories and identify potential upselling or bundling opportunities.

Through this exploration, we hope to contribute to the evolution of online retail by empowering businesses to better understand and cater to their customers' needs and preferences, ultimately fostering enhanced customer engagement, increased sales, and improved business strategies.

Algorithms¶

Association rules analysis related algorithms, such as Apriori and FP-growth tree algorithms that can be defined as a developed techniques that been used for the transactional data type to compute how much association is between data values and thier relative combinations, like if a customer is 70% to buy a milk how likley a customer will also buy bread. Here will use two main types of algorithms are being used: The Apriori and the FP Growth, where data are structured as shown in table 1.

Table 1. Example set of baskets. from Basket analysis and Association Rules

Referring the algorithm¶

From both "Data Mining: Concepts and Techniques" by Jiawei Han, Jian Pei, and Micheline Kamber, and the article "A Survey of Frequent Itemset Mining Algorithms" by Charu C. Aggarwal and Philip S. Yu, it becomes evident that the selection of association rule mining algorithms is intricately linked to the characteristics of the dataset.

In accordance with the findings presented in these sources:

  • For sparse datasets (many transactions with few items per transaction): FP-Growth can be more efficient due to its pattern-based approach and avoidance of candidate generation in later iterations.
  • For dense datasets (many items per transaction): Apriori might be preferable as it can leverage the monotonicity property for effective pruning.

Apriori algorithm¶

The Apriori algorithm (Agrawal & Srikant, 1994) stands as a foundational pillar in the field of association rule mining, offering an iterative approach to identifying frequent itemsets upon which association rules are built.

source: Apriori

Strengths of the Apriori Algorithm

  • Simplicity and Understandability: The Apriori algorithm is renowned for its intuitive and easy-to-understand design.
  • Data Scalability: While less efficient for massive datasets compared to algorithms like FP-Growth, Apriori remains a viable option for small to medium-sized datasets.

Fp-Growth Algorithm¶

The FP-Growth algorithm, introduced by Han, J., Pei, J., & Yin, Y. in their paper "Mining Frequent Patterns without Candidate Generation," offers a novel approach to association rule mining. It employs a compact data structure called the FP-Tree to efficiently mine frequent patterns without the need for candidate generation. This innovative technique has gained widespread adoption due to its ability to handle large-scale datasets and deliver superior performance compared to traditional algorithms like Apriori.

source: fp-growth

Strengths of FP-Growth Algorithm

The FP-Growth algorithm, as outlined by Han et al. (2000), possesses several strengths:

  • Efficiency: eliminates candidate generation, resulting in significantly reduced computational overhead compared to traditional algorithms like Apriori.
  • Compact Data Representation: The FP-Tree data structure enables efficient storage and traversal of transactional data, making FP-Growth well-suited for large datasets.
  • Scalability: can handle massive datasets with millions of transactions and thousands of items, showcasing its scalability and robustness.
  • Parallelization:can be parallelized for distributed processing across multiple computing nodes, further enhancing its scalability and efficiency.

Some Applications of Algorithms¶

  • Market basket analysis: Identifying frequently co-purchased items enables retailers to optimize product placement and recommend complementary products, ultimately enhancing customer experience and sales (Han, Pei & Kamber, 2011).
  • Customer segmentation: Grouping customers based on their purchase patterns fosters targeted marketing campaigns and personalized recommendations (Han, Pei & Kamber, 2011).
  • Fraud detection: Identifying unusual itemsets can aid in detecting fraudulent transactions (Han, Pei & Kamber, 2011).

Understanding Support, Confidence, and Lift¶

Three fundamental computations in association rule mining are support, confidence, and lift:

  • Support (S): Measures the frequency of an itemset within the dataset. It reflects how often a particular combination of items appears together.

    $$ support(A \rightarrow C) = support(A \cup C) \longrightarrow \: (range [0,1]) $$

  • Confidence (C): Indicates the likelihood of the consequent (right-hand side) occurring, given the antecedent (left-hand side). High confidence implies a strong rule.

    $$ confidence(A \rightarrow C) = \frac{support(A \rightarrow C)}{support(A)} \longrightarrow \: (range [0,1]) $$

  • Lift (L): Measures the strength of association between the antecedent and consequent, taking into account the overall frequency of the consequent. Lift greater than 1 suggests a positive association.

    $$ lift(A \rightarrow C) = \frac{confidence(A \rightarrow C)}{support(C)} \longrightarrow \: (range [0, \infty]) $$

Dataset Selection¶

This dataset contains transactional data from 01/12/2010 to 09/12/2011 for a UK-based online retail business specializing in unique all-occasion gifts. The company's customer base includes wholesalers.

Attributes¶

  • InvoiceNo: Unique 6-digit transaction number. Prefix 'c' indicates cancellation.
  • StockCode: Distinct 5-digit product code.
  • Description: Nominal product name description.
  • Quantity: Numeric, quantity of each product per transaction.
  • InvoiceDate: Numeric timestamp indicating date and time of the invoice.
  • UnitPrice: Numeric, price per unit in British pound sterling.
  • CustomerID: Nominal, 5-digit unique customer identifier.
  • Country: Nominal, name of the country where the customer resides.

Key findings:

  • Quantity distribution: The data reveals a right-skewed distribution for invoice quantities. This indicates that most invoices involve relatively small quantities, while a smaller number of invoices have significantly larger quantities.
  • Median vs. mean: The median quantity (around 3) is considerably lower than the mean quantity (around 9.5). This difference suggests a positive skew, potentially influenced by a few outliers with exceptionally high quantities.
  • Outliers: Both the minimum (-80,995) and maximum (80,995) quantities appear to be outliers. These negative and extremely high values might represent returns, adjustments, or exceptional bulk orders and require further investigation to ensure data accuracy and avoid skewing the analysis.
  • Quartiles: Examining the quartiles, we see that 25% of invoices have quantities less than or equal to 1, while 75% have quantities less than or equal to 10. This further reinforces the predominance of smaller quantities compared to larger ones.

itemset_coded = itemset.applymap(lambda x: 1 if x >= 1 else 0)

Association rules primarily aim to discover patterns of co-occurrence between multiple items purchased together. Filtering out invoices with only 1 item eliminates them from the analysis as they don't offer any insights into relationships between different products.

Most association rule mining algorithms utilize a minimum support threshold. This threshold defines the minimum number of times an itemset (group of items) needs to appear in the data to be considered "frequent" and eligible for further analysis as a potential rule. Filtering for invoices with 2+ items ensures that we have a sufficient number of items per transaction to potentially discover frequent itemsets that meet the minimum support requirement.

Generating Frequent Itemsets¶

Frequent itemsets, the cornerstone of association rule mining, represent groups of items that frequently appear together in transactions within a dataset. Uncovering these frequent patterns helps identify potential associations between items, providing valuable insights into customer buying habits and product relationships.

Referring the suitable algorithm¶

My Recommendation:

  1. High average number of items per transaction:

    • The average of 20.92 items per transaction is significantly higher than the typical threshold for a sparse dataset.
    • This indicates that your data has a high number of items co-occurring in each transaction.

  2. Data distribution:

    • The fact that most of your data lies in the 0-100 bin further supports the conclusion that it is dense.
    • Sparse datasets typically have a more skewed distribution, with a majority of transactions having few items and a small number of transactions having a large number of items.

Apriori might be a more suitable algorithm for generating frequent itemsets. This is because:

  • Apriori can leverage the monotonicity property for effective pruning, which can be particularly beneficial for dense datasets.
  • FP-Growth, while efficient for sparse datasets, might not offer significant advantages in this case due to the high number of items per transaction.

Setting the Parameters for Apriori¶

Support:

  • At first, I want to test with support = 0.03, means that itemset is considered frequent if it appears in at least 3% (426 transactions) of all transactions in dataset.Interesting findings at this threshold might reveal popular product combinations or frequently occurring purchasing patterns among customers.
  • Then, I use support = 0.01 means that Lowering the support threshold to 0.01 expands our search to identify additional interesting patterns in the dataset, requiring itemsets to be present in at least 1% of all transactions (equivalent to 142 transactions).

metric="lift":

  • min_threshold = 1.1 ( means lift>1). Lift measures the strength of an association rule compared to the independence of the items. A lift of 1 indicates no association, while values greater than 1 indicate a positive association (items are bought together more often than expected by chance).

.

# Create a directed graph
G = nx.DiGraph()

plt.figure(figsize=(9, 10))
# Add nodes for antecedents and consequents
for i, row in lift_table.iterrows():
    G.add_node(row['Antecedents'], color='lightblue')
    G.add_node(row['Consequents'], color='yellow')
    G.add_edge(row['Antecedents'], row['Consequents'], weight=row['Lift'])

    # Draw the graph
pos = nx.spring_layout(G, seed=732)  # Set the seed for reproducibility
nx.draw(G, pos, with_labels=False,node_size=1000, node_color=[color for node, color in nx.get_node_attributes(G, 'color').items()], edge_color='gray', arrowsize=20)

# Add labels for nodes (items) with smaller font size
nx.draw_networkx_labels(G, pos, labels={n: n for n in G.nodes()}, font_size=8)


# Add labels for support and lift below the edges
for edge in G.edges():
    lift = G.edges[(edge[0], edge[1])]['weight']
    x = 0.5 * (pos[edge[0]][0] + pos[edge[1]][0])
    y = 0.5 * (pos[edge[0]][1] + pos[edge[1]][1])
    plt.text(x, y, f"- - - -> {lift:.2f}", fontsize=8, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='bottom', rotation=90)
    
# Add title
plt.title('Association Rules Graph of Apriori Algorithm')

# Show plot
plt.show()

Insights

  • The graph reveals a positive trend between confidence and support. As we move from the bottom left (low support, low confidence) to the top right (high support, high confidence), we see that rules with more frequent co-occurrences of items (higher support) tend to have stronger associations between those items (higher confidence). This reinforces the notion that when customers consistently buy both item X and item Y together, there's a greater likelihood that their purchase of X will be accompanied by Y.

  • While confidence generally increases with increasing support, the rate of increase slows down at higher support levels. This suggests that rules with very high support are more likely to be confident, but additional support doesn't always lead to significantly higher confidence. In other words, the most frequent buying patterns are also likely to be the most reliable indicators of association, but further increases in purchase frequency may not necessarily translate into proportionally stronger confidence.

  • The data points are not perfectly aligned, indicating that support and confidence are not completely deterministic. This implies that other factors beyond just frequency can influence the strength of associations between items. These factors could include:

    • Promotions: Special offers or discounts might temporarily increase the co-purchase of certain items, even if they wouldn't be bought together as frequently under regular circumstances.
    • Seasonality: Changes in seasons might influence buying habits, leading to temporary associations between items that are relevant during specific periods (e.g., winter clothes and hot beverages).
      • Customer preferences: Individual preferences or specific needs might also play a role. For example, a customer buying a gardening tool might be more likely to also purchase gloves if they have a history of buying these items together, even if this isn't a common pattern overall.

Visulizing Association rules¶

Networkx¶

An intriguing approach to analyzing such data involves utilizing network analysis plots to visualize the relationships between each feature and its corresponding compound feature within the dataset. In this case, we employed the NetworkX module to plot the top 100 strongest relations.

To ensure clarity and aesthetics in representing the vast array of data points, we opted for the 'planar_layout' layout. Additionally, to streamline the visualization process, we utilized a lambda function to convert the frozenset objects to strings, eliminating the need to print frozensets with each created node. This enables a more intuitive and visually appealing depiction of the relationships between features and their compound counterparts within the dataset.

In [57]:
apriori_rules['antecedents'] = apriori_rules.antecedents.apply(lambda x: next(iter(x)))
apriori_rules['consequents'] = apriori_rules.consequents.apply(lambda x: next(iter(x)))

# Filter the top 100 association rules based on lift
top_100_rules = apriori_rules.sort_values(by='lift', ascending=False).head(100)

# Create the graph
edges = nx.from_pandas_edgelist(top_100_rules, source='antecedents', target='consequents', edge_attr=None)

# Plot the graph
plt.subplots(figsize=(60, 80))
plt.suptitle('Top 100 association rules based on lift', fontsize=50, fontweight='bold')
pos = nx.spring_layout(edges)  # You can choose a layout based on your preference
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(edges, pos, node_size=2000, alpha=0.7, node_color='tomato')
nx.draw_networkx_edges(edges, pos, width=6, alpha=0.2, edge_color='indigo')
nx.draw_networkx_labels(edges, pos, font_size=43, font_weight='bold')
plt.grid()
plt.axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observations:

  • Densely connected areas: The presence of densely connected regions in the graph suggests potential clusters of items that frequently appear together in association rules. These clusters could represent:

    • Complementary products: Items that customers often buy together, such as gardening tools and gloves.
    • Substitute products: Items that serve similar purposes and might be bought alternatively, depending on factors like price or availability.
    • Category relationships: Groups of items belonging to the same category, like different types of vegetables or beverages.

  • Central nodes: Nodes with a higher number of connections (more edges) might represent frequently purchased items or key items involved in many association rules. These could be:

    • Staple items: Products that customers buy regularly, forming the core of their shopping habits.
    • Versatile items: Items that can be used in various contexts and might be paired with diverse products.

Conclusion¶

This project underscores the transformative potential of association rule mining in uncovering latent connections and patterns within complex datasets:

  • Illuminating hidden relationships: Through association rule mining, our analysis has unearthed surprising correlations between seemingly unrelated products. Notably, the strong associations identified among specific teacup variations and the "HERB MARKER" products highlight the capacity of this methodology to reveal previously unseen connections in customer purchasing behavior.

    • Teacup and saucer sets: Customers purchasing a single teacup and saucer are likely to buy the other two color variations and a matching cake stand.
    • Herbs: Thyme, rosemary, and mint form a strong cluster, with customers buying any two from this trio highly likely to also purchase the third one.

  • Revealing product clusters: Our findings elucidate the clustering phenomenon evident in the association rules, such as the emergence of distinct product clusters like the "herbs trio" comprising thyme, rosemary, and mint. These insights offer valuable insights into underlying product categories and customer preferences, providing a deeper understanding of consumer behavior and preferences.

  • Driving actionable strategies: Importantly, our analysis extends beyond mere observation by translating discovered associations into actionable insights for business strategies. Recommendations for targeted marketing, strategic product placement, and customer engagement strategies underscore the practical utility of these findings in optimizing sales performance and enhancing customer satisfaction.

Future Work¶

Temporal patterns exploration: Investigate temporal patterns in customer purchasing behavior, including seasonal fluctuations. By analyzing how buying patterns evolve over time, we can gain insights into time-sensitive associations and adjust marketing strategies accordingly to capitalize on seasonal trends.

Network analysis refinement: Further refine network analysis methodologies to uncover more intricate relationships between product categories. By delving deeper into network analysis, we can uncover hidden patterns in customer behavior and better understand the underlying dynamics driving purchasing decisions.

Implementation of recommendations: Build upon the identified associations to implement actionable strategies derived from these insights. This involves deploying targeted product recommendations and strategic product placement initiatives to influence customer purchasing behavior. Testing these strategies in real-world settings will allow us to validate their effectiveness and refine our approach to optimize business outcomes.
